MODELS:

In this doc I am only including the best models thus far. For full information on process of investigating alternate variable forms and model fits see Rules_model.Rmd

2. WINTER :

Predicting Likelihood that a herder household will reserve Winter Pastures

We built {#} multilevel statistical models with different levels of complexity to model pasture managment behavior of herder households. In all models, the dependent variable was the binary variable of whether a household reserves Winter and Spring pastures. Model 1 is a random-intercept model without an explanatory variables. We included Organizational effects in the model as a random component; the assumption is that there is more similarity in the practices of a houshold within an organization that between organizations. In this model the variance iof the dependent variable is parsed in to household level variance and organization-level variance. Eq. 1: \(y_{ij} = \gamma_{00} + U_{0j}\)

where \(y_i\) is the dependent variable measured at houhold \(i\) in organization \(j\). Model 1 was used as the baseline model to estimate the group-level variance in the dependent variable. We compared each model to an intercept-only model and models w random intercepts performed better in both instances. We assessed subsets of the independent/predictor variables via a stepwise method to explore the relative model fits across different combinations of predictors.

2.1 Null Model The estimate of the constant is the logit of the proportion Reserving Pastures: Testing null models w just the randon intercept specified, to see which of these accounts for the most var. None of these models are significant in and of themselves, acording to straight p-vals, but by examining the AIC/BIC across the models we can see that for the Winter Pastures there is variation across Soum and Org (more variation between than within) and
for the Spring Pastures there is more var across only Soums, not Org.
But no support for random intercepts by ecological zone (jives with results from other model runs).

[Based on these I am going to just go w Org as grouping var (random) for both w & sp]

nullw  <-  glm ( ResWint ~ 1 , data=td, family=binomial)   # AIC = 977
nullw.r <-  glmer( ResWint ~ 1 + (1|Org), data=td, family=binomial) #AIC = 947.2

####Takeaway: The data are best explained by a model that includes:
Tenure on Winter Pasture AND Camp, Rule formality and cognitive social capital.

BUT this form will not let us take random effects of Organization and/or Soum in to account, and we know from previous steps (see Rules_model.Rmd doc) that model fit improves with including random effect of Org, based on assumption that there may be more sim within group that among.

So, this is the same model as above, but w random effects of Org specified. Modelling with BOTH winter tenure parameters : Various attempts at models w ecological zone included as either fixed or random effect were not signif and/or performed poorly. Only ez3=Eastern Steppe was ever signif.

The odds of a hh reserving winter pasture are lower if there are not Rules in place regarding timing of grazing of (winter pasture). However, the odds of the hh reserving pasture increase with increasing tenure on the winter camp. The odds of the household reserving pasture increases the most with increases in Social Capital.
The conditional R2 describes the proportion of variance explained by both the fixed and random factors morginal is just fixed factors.

But, while we can run the full models w random effect by Org specified and extract those coeffs (see above work) that doesnt get us differences by ez which might be important, and the models wont run w random effect by ez also included (wont converge)[this may be bc of issues revealed in the Steppe-only model below?] [Seeking help on this from another person]

So, maybe we look at these separately then. -either by ecological zone separately to see if diff models needed for diff zones. AND/or -to assess the relative impacts of Rules across the zones.
